Assign ASVs to strains in the A1 data

Michael McLaren

2020-08-03

Goal: Create a table with a row for each ASV from a (planned) inoculum strain, the additional E. coli ASV found in the fecal samples, and the Zymo strains.

Setup

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(cowplot)
library(ggridges)
library(ggbeeswarm)
library(ggforce)
library(speedyseq)
import::from(metacal, mutate_by)
theme_set(theme_cowplot(12))
my_psmelt <- function(physeq) {
  speedyseq::psmelt(physeq) %>%
    as_tibble %>%
    rename(taxon = OTU, sample = Sample, abundance = Abundance)
}
as_tibble.phyloseq <- function(x) {
  x %>% my_psmelt
}
as_tibble.sample_data <- function(x) {
  x %>% as("data.frame") %>% as_tibble(rownames = "sample")
}
as_tibble.taxonomyTable <- function(x) {
  x %>% as("matrix") %>% as_tibble(rownames = "taxon")
}
as_tibble.XStringSet <- function(x) {
  x %>% as.character %>% enframe("taxon", "sequence")
}

Load the reference 16S sequences for inoculum strains, T. mobilis strain, and the Zymo mock strains. Simplify the sequence names, and parse the original names into a table with information about each sequence.

ref_dna <- here("strain-info", "inoculum-tmob-zymo-16s.fasta") %>%
  Biostrings::readDNAStringSet()
# Table with strain info for each reference sequence
seq_names <- names(ref_dna)
ref_tb <- tibble(name = seq_names) %>%
  separate(name, 
    into = c("seqid", "genus", "species", "strain"), 
    sep = " ", 
    extra = "merge",
    remove = TRUE
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    source = case_when(
      strain == "Zymo" ~ "Zymo DNA mock",
      species == "mobilis" ~ "T. mobilis",
      TRUE ~ "inoculum"
    )
  )
ref_tb %>% head
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   seqid      genus       species          strain                  source

# Set the names to just the seqid's
names(ref_dna) <- names(ref_dna) %>%
  str_extract("^\\S+")

Filter low-abundance ASVs

A large fraction of ASVs have very low total abundance (read count),

taxa_sums(ps) %>%
  enframe %>%
  ggplot(aes(value)) +
  stat_ecdf(geom = "step") +
  scale_x_log10(breaks = c(2, 10, 1e2, 1e3))

Those with less than 10 reads are unlikely to be of interest to us. Some are spurious ASV calls derived from sequencing errors from high-abundance ASVs; others may be low-level reagent or other types of contamination. Either way they are too rare to interfere with interpretations our our analyses if we simply filter them out.

To reduce the number of ASVs we need to consider, lets filter to those in at least 10 total reads,

ps0 <- ps %>%
  filter_taxa2(~sum(.) >= 10) %>%
  print
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 52 taxa and 96 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 96 samples by 22 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 52 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## refseq()      DNAStringSet:      [ 52 reference sequences ]

Get a pairwise distance matrix between all ASVs and reference sequences,

dna <- c(refseq(ps0), ref_dna)
nproc <- 4
aln <- DECIPHER::AlignSeqs(dna, processors = nproc, verbose = FALSE)
d <- DECIPHER::DistanceMatrix(aln, processors = nproc, verbose = FALSE)
dtb <- d %>%
  as.dist(diag = FALSE, upper = TRUE) %>%
  broom::tidy() %>%
  mutate_at(vars(starts_with("item")), as.character)

First pass: Strain assignment by exact matching

Goal: Assign ASVs to strains using reference sequences. As a first pass, Ill look for exact matches between the ASVs and the reference 16S sequences.

unique_or_na <- function(x) {
  if (length(unique(x)) == 1)
    x[[1]]
  else
    NA_character_
}
assignments <- dtb %>%
  filter(distance == 0) %>%
  filter(str_detect(item1, "A1_ASV"), !str_detect(item2, "A1_ASV")) %>%
  left_join(ref_tb, by = c("item2" = "seqid")) %>%
  rename(asv = item1) %>%
  group_by(asv) %>%
  summarize(
    genus = unique_or_na(genus),
    species = unique_or_na(species),
    # strain = unique(strain) %>% paste(collapse = ";")
    source = unique(source) %>% paste(collapse = ";")
  ) %>%
  arrange(source,genus,species) %>%
  print(n=Inf)

Find other candidate ASVs

Unfortunately the 16S reference sequences I was able to find do not always match every ASV that appears to be derived from these organisms, even for the Zymo strains where the reference sequences are from the company. ASVs that are highly similar (~< 1% diverged) may be from the same genomes as the identified ASVs.

Example: Bacteroides ovatus

ASVs from the same genome should have highly correlated proportions, since they appear biologically in a constant ratio. Also, if there is no intragenomic bias then when we multiply the strains 16S copy number by the proportion of one ASVs reads out of all ASVs reads from the same organism we should get an integer. In my experience, there are usually only 2 ASVs from the same genome and one of those is much more abundant than the other, suggesting that one ASV appears in the large majority of 16S copies. Here is a clear example with Bacteroides ovatus.

ps0 %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV1", "A1_ASV8"), .) %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  # prop_and_cor_plot
  id_plot(cn = 5)

Systematically find candidate ASVs from same genome

To find candidates, lets first get all pairs of ASVs within 3% divergence (<= 4 nucleotide changes) from each other.

candidates <- dtb %>%
  filter(
    item1 %in% taxa_names(ps0), 
    item2 %in% taxa_names(ps0),
    distance < 0.03
  ) %>%
  arrange(distance)
candidates %>%
  filter(item1 < item2) %>%
  left_join(tax %>% select(taxon, genus, species), 
    by = c("item1" = "taxon")) %>%
  left_join(tax %>% select(taxon, genus, species), 
    by = c("item2" = "taxon"),
    suffix = c("1", "2")
  ) %>%
  print(n=Inf)
## # A tibble: 16 x 7

Focus on cases of interest

For now I will ignore contaminants and just worry about the inoculum and zymo strains (T. mobilis only gave 1 ASV).

Find pairs where distance < 0.01 and at least one ASV was assigned,

focal_candidates <- candidates %>%
  filter(item1 %in% assignments$asv, distance < 0.01) %>%
  left_join(assignments, by = c("item1" = "asv")) %>%
  print

Escherichia coli. Conclusion: Complex / unclear
ps0 %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("DNA mock", "inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  # subset_taxa(genus == "Escherichia/Shigella") %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV2", "A1_ASV14"), .) %>%
  id_plot(cn = 7)

The first two rows suggest that the E. coli in the fecal samples carries both ASV2 and ASV14, but the E. coli in the inoculum only carries ASV2. However, the CN plot (bottom row) does not show integer numbers, suggesting that ASV2 and ASV14 might be highly correlated in the fecal samples but not in fact in the same genome. E.g., the fecal samples were perhaps colonized by the inoculum E. coli and another closely related organism.

Roseburia intestinalis. Conclusion: Same genome
ps0 %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  # subset_taxa(genus == "Roseburia") %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV9", "A1_ASV17"), .) %>%
  id_plot(cn = 6)

Barnesiella intestinihominis. Conclusion: Same genome
ps0 %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV19", "A1_ASV20"), .) %>%
  id_plot(cn = 4, min_prop = 1e-5)
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (position_quasirandom).

Here the answer is less obvious. However, the correlation in the fecal samples is very high, and the abundance in the inoculum samples is to low to make anything out of. Meanwhile, the CN of 4 is from a draft genome and might not be reliable. A CN of 5 gives a reasonably close fit to integer number in the fecal samples in row 3. Finally, both ASVs matched reference sequences for the expected strain, so we can safely conclude these are in the same genome.

Bacteroides ovatus (shown above). Conclusion: Same genome
Salmonella enterica (Zymo): Same genome
ps0 %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("DNA mock", "inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV23", "A1_ASV29"), .) %>%
  id_plot(cn = 7, min_prop = 1e-5)
## Warning: Removed 106 rows containing missing values
## (position_quasirandom).
## Warning: Removed 58 rows containing missing values (position_quasirandom).

In this case, we expect all the reads outside the DNA mock to be cross-contamination / index-hopping. Though we only have one meaningful data point, the fact that the ratio is nearly exactly 6:1 suggests these ASVs are from the same genome.

Bacillus ASV22 and ASV24: Different genomes
ps0 %>%
  subset_samples(specimen_type %in% c("DNA mock", "inoculum", "fecal")) %>%
  prune_taxa(c("A1_ASV22", "A1_ASV24"), .) %>%
  id_plot(cn = 10, min_prop = 1e-5)
## Warning: Removed 86 rows containing missing values (position_quasirandom).

ASV22 was assigned to the Zymo reference sequence for Bacillus subtilis, while ASV24 did not match a reference sequence. From the plot it appears that

  • ASV22 is the only ASV for the Zymo B. subtilis strain, is biologically absent in other samples and occasionally appears at very low frequency due to cross-contamination
  • ASV24 is a contaminant of the inoculum and is biologically absent in all other samples, occasionally appearing in fecal samples due to cross-contamination

Manual assignments

For now I will focus on ASVs from (intentional) inoculum strains the Zymo strains and ignore contaminants (unless they are in the fecal samples; see below).

assignments_new <- focal_candidates %>%
  filter(
    genus %in% c("Escherichia", "Roseburia", "Salmonella", "Bacteroides")
  ) %>%
  rename(asv = item2) %>%
  select(-item1, -distance) %>%
  mutate(source = ifelse(asv == "A1_ASV14", "fecal", source))
assignments_full <- bind_rows(assignments, assignments_new) %>%
  arrange(source, genus, species) %>%
  print(n = Inf)

Save along with the amplicon sequences,

assignments_full %>%
  rename(feature_id = asv) %>%
  left_join(refseq(ps) %>% as_tibble, by = c(feature_id = "taxon")) %>%
  write_csv(here("results", "a1", "a1-asv-strain-assignments.csv"))
